                                                <p> <hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 4.&#8212;<name type="person" key="xxx">Corporal Ellsby McCoy</name>, <name type="organization" key="xxx">Co. D, 20th Maine Volunteers</name>, aged 19 years, was
                                                                wounded at <name type="battle">Poplar Grove Church, Virginia</name>, <date type="injury" when="1864-09-30">September 30th, 1864</date>, by a conoidal ball, which
                                                  entered the chest on the left side, fractured the
                                                  fourth rib, and, glancing, lodged in the axilla on
                                                  the same side. He was taken to the field hospital
                                                  of the Fifth Corps, and, on <date type="transfer" when="1864-10-07">October 7th</date>, was transferred to <name type="hospital" key="176">Lincoln Hospital</name>, Washington. On <date type="operation" when="1864-10-20">October
                                                                  20th</date>, <name type="person" key="243">Assistant Surgeon J. C. McKee</name>, <name type="organization" key="190">U. S. A.</name>,
                                                  administered chloroform and extracted the ball
                                                  through an incision made along the border of the
                                                  lattissimus dorsi muscle; the end of the fractured
                                                  rib was also resected. The patient was discharged
                                                  from service <date type="servicedischarge" when="1865-03-23">March 23d, 1865</date>. He is not a pensioner. </p>
                                                
